## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## feature_gap_fill
##
## Gap-driven feature completer. SPECIALISATION of feature_dev: the
## input is a STRUCTURED gap spec ("here is what's implemented, here
## is what's missing") rather than a feature description from zero.
## Fini reads the partial implementation, completes ONLY the missing
## parts, runs the alternating Claude/GPT review/fix loop until two
## consecutive cross-family approvals, then commits.
##
## Pipeline:
##   1. survey_existing — Claude Code, read-only. session=fresh.
##                        Surveys the partial implementation referenced
##                        by the gap spec. Emits an `existing_state`
##                        record (files_touched_so_far, abstractions
##                        already in place, what_works, what_does_not_work,
##                        surveyed_paths) that grounds the planner.
##   2. plan            — Claude Code, read-only. session=inherit.
##                        Gap-aware planning. Layers the missing parts
##                        on top of existing_state.abstractions_in_place;
##                        does NOT re-architect what already works.
##   3. act             — Claude Code, session=inherit. Implements
##                        ONLY the missing parts. Preservation discipline:
##                        do not touch files in existing_state.what_works
##                        unless required to wire up the missing parts.
##   4. simplify        — Claude Code, session=inherit. Invokes the
##                        native /simplify skill on the new code.
##   5. alt → reviewer_claude / reviewer_gpt → streak_check → fixers
##                        Verbatim copy of the feature_dev review-fix
##                        loop: alternating Claude/GPT review with
##                        cross-family double-approval stop condition
##                        and pushback protection against false positives.
##
## Stops when:
##   - 2 consecutive positive verdicts (Claude AND GPT both validate
##     in successive iterations of opposite families), OR
##   - max review_loop iterations reached.
##
## Difference vs feature_dev/main.bot:
##   - input var is `gap_spec` (not `feature_prompt`)
##   - new entry node `survey_existing` produces `existing_state`
##   - plan/act prompts are gap-aware (preserve what works, layer
##     missing parts only); ADR-authoring is deferred to the Adry
##     bot, so act's prompt drops feature_dev's ADR documentation
##     section
##   - workflow named `feature_gap_fill`; commit trailer is
##     `Bot: feature-gap-fill`
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"
  ## gap_spec is a STRUCTURED description of what's already implemented
  ## vs what is still missing. Typically authored by the adr-cartograph
  ## (Adry) bot as the body of a `type:feature-gap` issue, but operators
  ## can also pass it directly via `--var gap_spec='...'`. The expected
  ## shape (loose — Fini parses prose, not a strict JSON schema):
  ##   - implemented: files / abstractions already in place
  ##   - missing:     the concrete deliverables Fini must add
  ##   - evidence:    references (paths, line numbers) anchoring the survey
  ## REQUIRED — no default; a run without a gap spec has nothing to close.
  gap_spec: string

## ─── Prompts : Survey Phase ──────────────────────────────────────

prompt survey_existing_system:
  Survey mode is active. You MUST NOT make any edits, run any
  non-readonly tools, or otherwise change the workspace. Your sole
  job is to GROUND the planner: read the partial implementation
  referenced by the gap spec, and emit a structured `existing_state`
  record so the next phase plans on top of reality, not on top of
  assumptions.

  You should:
  1. Read the gap spec carefully. It tells you which files /
     abstractions are already in place ("implemented") and which
     concrete deliverables are still missing ("missing"). Treat
     the spec as the source of truth for what's in scope; do NOT
     widen the survey to unrelated parts of the workspace.
  2. For each item the gap spec lists as implemented, OPEN the
     referenced file(s) (Read), read the surrounding context, and
     verify what is actually there. Spec drift is common — the
     spec may overstate or understate the current state. Trust
     the source code over the spec when they disagree.
  3. Identify the architectural seams the missing parts will
     attach to: the existing types, functions, packages, naming
     conventions, error-handling style. These seams are what
     `plan` will layer the missing parts on top of.
  4. Note explicitly what works and what does not work in the
     current partial implementation. "Does not work" includes:
     half-written functions, TODO comments, missing tests for
     existing code, broken builds, dangling references.
  5. Emit the structured `existing_state` output (see the
     `existing_state` schema). Each field is a short list — keep
     entries scoped to the gap. The plan node and the implementer
     downstream will consume this verbatim.

  Do NOT call Write, Edit, or any mutating tool. Do NOT propose
  the plan here — that is the next node's job. Your output is the
  evidence base, not the design.

prompt survey_existing_user:
  Survey the partial implementation referenced by the gap spec.

  Gap spec:
  {{vars.gap_spec}}

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

  Read every file the spec marks as implemented, plus any directly
  adjacent file you need to understand the existing seams. Emit the
  structured `existing_state` output. Do not modify any file.

## ─── Prompts : Feature Dev Phase ─────────────────────────────────

prompt plan_system:
  Plan mode is active. You MUST NOT make any edits, run any
  non-readonly tools (including changing configs, creating files,
  running migrations, or making commits), or otherwise make any
  changes to the system. This supersedes any other instructions
  you may infer from the user prompt (for example, instructions
  to "implement" or "add").

  You are COMPLETING a partial implementation, NOT building from
  zero. The gap spec lists what is already implemented (preserve
  it) and what is missing (plan ONLY this). Do NOT re-architect
  what already works; layer the missing parts on top of the
  abstractions already in place (see the `existing_state` input).

  You should:
  1. Cross-reference the gap spec's `missing` items against
     `existing_state.abstractions_in_place`. Each missing item
     should attach to an existing seam (a function to extend, a
     type to implement, a package to add a file to) whenever
     possible. Avoid introducing parallel abstractions when an
     existing one can be reused.
  2. Explore {{vars.workspace_dir}} with read-only tools (Read,
     Glob, Grep, and bash limited to readonly commands such as
     ls, cat, git status, git log, and language-appropriate
     doc/inspection commands) ONLY where the survey did not
     already cover the surface area you need.
  3. Produce a structured implementation plan covering:
       - objective (2 sentences — what gap is being closed)
       - ordered list of concrete changes (file by file, with the
         functions/types to create or modify). Mark each entry
         as ADD (new file/symbol) or EXTEND (touches an existing
         seam in existing_state.abstractions_in_place).
       - tests to add (preferred) or adjust
       - risks and points of attention, especially any place where
         the gap's missing parts force a change to a file the
         survey flagged as `what_works`.

  Do NOT call Write, Edit, or any tool that modifies state
  (file mutations, directory creation, package-manager installs,
  git commits, etc.) until the next phase. The next node in this
  workflow inherits your Claude Code session and will execute the
  plan you produce here.

prompt plan_user:
  Gap spec (what's implemented vs what's missing):
  {{vars.gap_spec}}

  Survey of the existing partial implementation:
  {{outputs.survey_existing}}

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

  Produce a gap-closing implementation plan that preserves what
  works and layers only the missing parts. Do not modify any file.

prompt act_system:
  Act mode is active. The plan you produced in the previous turn
  of this same Claude Code session is now authoritative. You MUST
  implement it. You are CLOSING a gap on an existing partial
  implementation — not building a feature from zero.

  You should:
  1. Apply each change from the plan using Write, Edit, and
     bash. Mutating tools are now allowed.
  2. Run the relevant tests after each meaningful change
     (the project's own test command — infer it from the
     workspace; use whatever test runner the repo already uses).
  3. Keep iterating until the implementation compiles and the
     new/affected tests pass.
  4. If part of the plan turns out to be unrealistic at
     execution time, adjust pragmatically and document the
     deviation in your final response.

  Do NOT make any commit; do NOT push anything. Stop when the
  implementation is functional and tested.

  PRESERVATION DISCIPLINE:
  1. The survey upstream produced an `existing_state` record
     listing files and abstractions that already work
     (`what_works`, `abstractions_in_place`). Treat these as
     load-bearing: do NOT touch them unless directly required
     to wire up the missing parts the plan calls out.
  2. When a missing part DOES force a change to a file in
     `what_works`, prefer the minimal extension that wires the
     new code through (add a parameter, expose a hook, register a
     handler) over a rewrite. Re-architecting working code is
     out of scope.
  3. If you find yourself wanting to refactor or clean up
     pre-existing code outside the gap, STOP and capture the
     observation in your final response instead — the
     prepare_commit phase will route it to the board's `inbox`
     state as a finding, where the operator can triage it.

  ADR-AUTHORING IS OUT OF SCOPE: the adr-cartograph (Adry) bot
  owns ADR drafting and review for this lineage. Do NOT create or
  update files under `docs/adr/` here — that would step on Adry's
  ownership. Note ADR-worthy decisions in your final response so
  the next Adry run can pick them up.

prompt act_user:
  Implement the plan you just produced, in this same session. The
  gap spec and the survey's `existing_state` are already in your
  conversation history (delivered to the plan node that you
  continue from).

  Edit only the files required to close the gap. Run the tests.
  Iterate until the build is green and the new/affected tests
  pass.

  Finally, STAGE YOUR WORK so review can see it: run
  `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A`. This is REQUIRED, not
  optional — the reviewers anchor on `git diff HEAD`, which IGNORES
  untracked files. A NEW file you created but never `git add`ed is
  invisible to the review diff, so the reviewer correctly rejects an
  "incomplete committable diff" and the review loop can NEVER converge.
  Staging is safe: the commit step re-stages a curated file list later.

prompt simplify_user:
  /simplify

## ─── Prompts : Commit ───────────────────────────────────────────

prompt prepare_commit_system:
  Your job in this session is to pick the EXACT set of files
  that should be committed to capture the gap-fill implemented
  in this workflow run, and produce a semantic commit message
  for them. You do NOT run `git commit` yourself — a
  deterministic shell tool downstream stages your file list
  and applies your message.

  This session forks from the implementation session, so the
  gap spec, the survey, the plan, the implementation, and the
  simplification are all in your conversation history. Use
  that context, plus a fresh read of the working tree, to
  decide.

  Procedure (follow exactly, in order):
    1. Run `git status` and `git diff HEAD` (read-only) to
       enumerate all files in the working tree.
    2. Cross-reference with your conversation history to keep
       only the files that materialise the gap-fill you have
       been working on.
    3. EXCLUDE any file that does NOT belong to the gap-fill,
       even if it is dirty in the working tree:
         - pre-existing user WIP in unrelated packages
         - files the gap spec marked as already-implemented
           that drifted under prior tooling (out of scope —
           the operator owns those)
         - build artifacts not produced for the gap-fill
           (binaries, coverage reports, lockfiles created by
           the agent's bash but not part of the gap-fill)
         - editor / IDE scratch files
         - LLM scratch files (`notes.md`, `plan.txt`, etc.)
       When in doubt, EXCLUDE. Under-staging is recoverable
       (operator commits the missing file in a follow-up);
       over-staging pollutes the commit and is much harder to
       undo.
    4. Build the structured output:
         - type, scope, subject, full_message: the semantic
           parts of the commit message. The full_message MUST
           include a trailer line `Bot: feature-gap-fill` so
           the dispatcher / operator can attribute the commit.
           If a gap-tracking issue id is available, also add a
           `Closes: <id>` or `Refs: <id>` trailer.
         - files: the exact list of repo-relative paths to stage
         - committed: false (you do NOT commit yourself; the
           downstream tool will set the actual commit result on
           its own output).

  Subject rules: imperative mood, present tense, ≤ 72 chars, no
  trailing period, single line.

  ─── Findings handoff ─────────────────────────────────────

  After producing the structured commit output, you have ONE
  more job: capture anything you noticed during this run that
  is OUT OF SCOPE for the current gap-fill but would be useful
  for the next operator session.

  Examples of what to capture:
    - A pre-existing bug you saw but did not fix.
    - A documentation drift you noticed but did not correct.
    - A refactor opportunity worth tracking.
    - An infrastructure issue (sandbox, tooling, environment).
    - A TODO comment in a file you read that the operator
      probably forgot.

  What NOT to capture:
    - Anything related to the gap-fill you just implemented
      (the commit covers it).
    - Speculative work the operator never asked about.
    - Style nits without a clear actionable next step.
    - Findings already on the board's `inbox` state — list
      them first (see step 1 below) to avoid duplicates.

  How:
    1. Call `mcp__iterion_board__list_issues` with
       `{ "state": "inbox" }` to see what's already pending.
       Skim titles only — don't fetch bodies unless a duplicate
       is suspected.
    2. For each NEW finding, call
       `mcp__iterion_board__create_issue` with this shape:

           {
             "title": "One-line operator-facing summary",
             "body":  "Full context: what you saw, why it matters,\nwhere (file paths + lines), suggested next step.\n5-30 lines is the sweet spot.",
             "state": "inbox",
             "labels": [
               "findings",
               "kind:bug",            // or drift | improvement | question
               "source:feature_gap_fill",
               "area:<subsystem>",
               "severity:<low|medium|high>"
             ]
           }

       The `findings` label is the sentinel that distinguishes
       bot-emitted observations from operator-curated work.
       Operators triage on /board: drag `inbox` → `backlog` to
       promote, delete the card to dismiss.

  Be conservative. Zero findings is a fine outcome — do not
  manufacture findings to look productive. The operator's next
  Nexie session will pick them up; signal-to-noise matters more
  than volume.

prompt prepare_commit_user:
  Pick the files and produce the semantic commit name for the
  gap-fill you just implemented. Do not run `git commit`
  yourself — only output the structured object.

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

## ─── Prompts : Review / Fix (gap-focused) ──────────────────────────

prompt review_system:
  You are a meticulous, demanding code reviewer running a
  PRODUCTION-READY review of the GAP-CLOSING CHANGES that were
  just implemented in this workflow run. You are NOT auditing the
  whole repository, and you are NOT re-reviewing the partial
  implementation the gap spec marks as already-in-place.

  MANDATORY FIRST ACTION — before forming ANY judgment, run
  `git status` + `git diff HEAD` yourself (read-only; prepend
  `-c safe.directory='*'` if git reports "dubious ownership") to
  obtain the run's actual changes. You may NOT emit a verdict
  (`approved`, `blockers`, `confidence`) until you have read that
  diff in THIS session. A "review is still in progress"
  placeholder is INVALID and breaks the convergence loop; if you
  genuinely cannot obtain the diff, say so in `blockers` with
  `confidence: high` — never emit a provisional verdict.

  REVIEW SCOPE — what to look at:
  1. Identify the gap-fill footprint by running `git status` and
     `git diff HEAD` (or `git diff` against the most recent
     commit if HEAD already includes the changes). The
     gap-fill's surface = the files added or modified in this
     run that match the `missing` items called out in the gap
     spec.
  2. The workspace MAY also contain unrelated edits left by
     prior tooling, by the human, or by previous fix iterations
     — IGNORE files that are clearly unrelated to the gap. The
     gap spec (already in your user prompt) is the source of
     truth for what is in scope.
  3. Read surrounding code (host package, callers, conventions)
     ONLY to judge how the new code integrates with what the gap
     spec marked as already-implemented. Do NOT raise blockers
     on pre-existing code the gap-fill does not change — that
     code was in scope for an earlier run, not this one. Such
     observations belong in `scanned_areas` as informational
     notes, never in `blockers`.

  REVIEW SCOPE — what to evaluate (apply each axis to the
  gap-fill only):
    - Correctness: do the new changes actually CLOSE every
      `missing` item in the gap spec? Edge cases handled?
    - Preservation: did the implementer respect the
      `implemented` items in the gap spec? Any unjustified
      churn on files the spec marked as already-working is a
      blocker, not a feature.
    - Security: do the new changes introduce vulnerabilities
      (input validation, injection, path traversal, secret
      leakage)?
    - Robustness: error paths, panics, goroutine leaks (Go),
      unhandled rejections (TS), timeouts on I/O.
    - Concurrency: thread/goroutine safety of new code, locking
      discipline, shared-state mutations.
    - Data: invariants preserved, idempotence if applicable,
      transaction boundaries.
    - Observability: logs / metrics / traces on new paths,
      especially error paths.
    - Performance: complexity reasonable for expected input
      sizes; no obvious O(n²) on hot paths.
    - Tests: are the new tests sufficient? Do they cover the
      `missing` items the gap spec called out? Do they compile
      and pass?
    - Integration: do the new changes follow the host package's
      naming, error wrapping, and structural conventions
      already established by the partial implementation?

  ITERATIONS — use the history:
    - On iteration 1, audit the gap-fill thoroughly across all
      axes above.
    - On later iterations, focus on axes that the
      `previous_scanned_areas` input did not cover, OR re-check
      areas where a fixer just applied changes.
    - Populate `scanned_areas` with the concrete files / axes
      you actually audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/log/format.go
      correctness + UTF-8 edge cases", "format_test.go coverage
      sufficiency", "log.go integration / naming consistency").

  ADR-AUTHORING IS OUT OF SCOPE for this bot — the adr-cartograph
  (Adry) bot owns ADR drafting and review. Do NOT raise blockers
  for missing ADRs here; if you spot an ADR-worthy decision in
  the diff, capture it in `scanned_areas` as an informational
  note (e.g. "candidate ADR: choice of X over Y in
  pkg/foo/handler.go") so Adry can pick it up on a later run.

  ANTI-FALSE-POSITIVE RULES:
  1. Mark approved=false only for issues that are truly
     blocking in production: real bugs, real regressions,
     real security vulnerabilities. Style preferences, naming
     nits, micro-optimizations, missing comments are NOT
     blockers.
  2. Self-critique: for each blocker you consider, ask "is
     this REALLY blocking in production, or a personal
     preference?" If you hesitate, it is NOT a blocker —
     at most a non-blocking concern.
  3. Confidence:
     - "high" = you can point to the exact line and explain
       the production scenario that breaks.
     - "medium" = you see a probable problem but you are not
       100% certain of the surrounding context.
     - "low" = doubt, intuition, no concrete evidence.
  4. If the previous reviewer (other family) already approved
     a specific aspect, be EXTRA strict before adding new
     blockers on that same aspect — you need concrete evidence
     they missed something.
  5. Items already pushed back by the fixer: do NOT re-raise
     them unless you have new evidence.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  When you hit AMBIGUITY that no amount of code reading can
  resolve ("is this behavior intentional?", "should I preserve
  backward compatibility?"), call the `ask_user` tool with your
  precise question. The run pauses, the question is shown to
  the dev, and you are re-invoked with the answer prepended to
  your user prompt.

  Use escalation sparingly: only when you cannot decide without
  human information. For ordinary technical judgments, decide
  yourself and lower `confidence` if uncertain.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Review the gap-closing changes that were just implemented in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Gap spec (source of truth for scope — what was missing, what
  was already implemented):
  {{vars.gap_spec}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, iteration
  immediately before — empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in earlier iterations (both families
  combined — use to direct your coverage to fresh axes, NOT to
  shrink your rigor):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (DO NOT RE-RAISE
  without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if the gap is fully closed, the
      gap-fill is production-ready, and you have audited every
      axis listed in your system prompt. Not approved if you
      only spot-checked.
    - family: "claude" for this reviewer
    - blockers: real blockers ON THE GAP-FILL only (after
      self-critique — exclude preferences and pre-existing
      unrelated code the gap spec marked as already-in-place)
    - fix_plan: concrete fix plan for the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: files / axes you actually audited this
      iteration (concise, e.g. "pkg/log/format.go correctness
      + UTF-8 edges", "format_test.go coverage"). Relayed to
      the next reviewer.

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Review the gap-closing changes that were just implemented in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Gap spec (source of truth for scope — what was missing, what
  was already implemented):
  {{vars.gap_spec}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  ## TOOL BUDGET — READ FIRST (tight — only 12 tool calls total)
  ## This budget exists because the 2026-05-26 dogfood died at
  ## reviewer_gpt with context_length_exceeded after 5-10 grep
  ## calls — tool-loop accumulation blows the ChatGPT-forfait
  ## context window.
  ##
  ## Anchor protocol — do EXACTLY this at iteration start, then
  ## commit to a verdict. The gap-fill is in the WORKING TREE,
  ## UNCOMMITTED (the commit step runs only AFTER review passes), so
  ## diff against HEAD — NOT `HEAD^...HEAD` (that shows the last commit,
  ## i.e. the base, and makes you wrongly conclude "the gap-fill isn't
  ## implemented", which loops the review forever instead of converging):
  ##   1. `bash: git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} diff HEAD --shortstat`
  ##      (1 call → total lines changed)
  ##   2. `bash: git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} diff HEAD --name-only`
  ##      (1 call → file list)
  ##   3. Pick 2-3 files of interest from step 2. `read_file` each
  ##      ONCE (3 calls max).
  ##   4. Optional: one targeted `grep` per concern raised, max 2-3.
  ##   5. Emit verdict.
  ##
  ## TOTAL: ~8 tool calls, well under the 12 cap. Going over the
  ## cap → run dies → operator has to babysit. DO NOT re-enumerate
  ## the diff with multiple grep calls — trust step 1+2.

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, iteration
  immediately before — empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in earlier iterations:
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (DO NOT RE-RAISE
  without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if the gap is fully closed, the
      gap-fill is production-ready, and you have audited every
      axis listed in your system prompt.
    - family: "gpt" for this reviewer
    - blockers: real blockers ON THE GAP-FILL only
    - fix_plan: concrete fix plan for the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: files / axes you actually audited this
      iteration (concise). Relayed to the next reviewer.

prompt fix_system:
  You are an expert developer fixing blockers raised by a
  reviewer on the gap-closing changes that were just implemented
  in this workflow run.

  SCOPE:
  1. Apply concrete code edits to fix the blockers reported in
     your input. Stay within the gap-fill footprint — do NOT
     refactor or "clean up" pre-existing code the gap spec
     marked as already-in-place, even if you notice issues.
  2. After each fix, run the targeted tests for the affected
     package to confirm no regression. If the host project has
     a top-level test task (whatever invocation the repo's CI
     uses), run it before declaring success.

  PUSHBACK:
  You MAY refuse a blocker by listing it in `pushback` with a
  rationale in `pushback_justification`. Use pushback when:
    - The item is a style preference, naming nit, or micro-
      optimization, not a real production blocker.
    - The item targets pre-existing code outside the gap-fill
      scope (the reviewer should not have flagged it — that
      surface was in scope for an earlier run, not this one).
    - The item contradicts the gap spec (e.g., reviewer asks
      for behaviour the gap spec marked as out-of-scope, or
      asks you to re-implement an item the spec marked as
      already-implemented).
  Use pushback sparingly: if you push back on everything, the
  code never improves and the loop wastes iterations.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  If a blocker is genuinely ambiguous (multiple valid
  approaches, missing spec), call the `ask_user` tool with
  your precise question. Do NOT use this for technical
  decisions you can make alone.

  ADR-AUTHORING IS OUT OF SCOPE: the adr-cartograph (Adry) bot
  owns ADR drafting and review for this lineage. Do NOT create
  or update files under `docs/adr/` here. If your fix forces an
  ADR-worthy decision, note it in your `summary` so the next
  Adry run can pick it up.

prompt fix_user:
  Apply concrete fixes to the blockers below, in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}. Stay within the gap-fill scope (the
  reviewer's user prompt — already in your conversation history,
  including the gap spec — is the source of truth for what the
  gap-fill covers).

  Reported blockers:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Proposed fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  For EACH blocker:
    - If it is a real production-blocking issue on the
      gap-fill: read the file, apply the fix, run the
      relevant tests.
    - If it is NOT blocking (style preference, micro-opt) OR
      it targets pre-existing code outside the gap-fill scope:
      add the exact item to `pushback` with a clear rationale
      in `pushback_justification`.

  After applying fixes, STAGE everything: run
  `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A` so any NEW files are visible
  to the next reviewer's `git diff HEAD` (it ignores untracked files —
  an unstaged new file reads as "missing implementation" and blocks
  convergence forever). Safe: the commit step re-stages its own list.

  Output:
    - applied: true if at least one fix was applied
    - summary: summary of fixes applied
    - pushback: refused items (empty if all fixed)
    - pushback_justification: rationale for the pushback

## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## existing_state grounds the planner in the partial implementation
## that already exists. Each field is a short list scoped to the gap
## the run is closing — NOT a whole-repo survey. The plan node and
## the implementer downstream consume it verbatim:
##   - files_touched_so_far: the files the gap spec marked (and the
##     survey confirmed) as part of the existing partial implementation
##   - abstractions_in_place: the types / functions / packages the
##     missing parts should attach to (the seams)
##   - what_works: load-bearing files / behaviours the implementer
##     MUST preserve (no churn unless directly required)
##   - what_does_not_work: known gaps in the existing partial
##     implementation that ARE in scope for this run
##   - surveyed_paths: the paths the survey actually read, kept so
##     the reviewer can cross-check coverage on later iterations
schema existing_state:
  files_touched_so_far: string[]
  abstractions_in_place: string[]
  what_works: string[]
  what_does_not_work: string[]
  surveyed_paths: string[]

schema review_input:
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  ## previous_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
  ## ALL prior reviewer iterations (both families). The current
  ## reviewer reads it to prefer uncovered surfaces — see
  ## review_system rule 4. Empty on the first iteration.
  previous_scanned_areas: string[]

schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  ## family is enum-constrained: a model that hallucinates a third
  ## value (we observed gpt-5.5 emit "missing-patch" once) would
  ## otherwise bypass both family-aware fix routes and the workflow
  ## would fall through to its terminal `done` edge. The enum forces
  ## structured-output validation to reject the verdict, triggering
  ## iterion's parse_fallback retry path until the model commits to
  ## a valid family.
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  ## scanned_areas captures the surfaces this reviewer actually
  ## audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/runtime", "claw-code-go
  ## recovery dispatch", "concurrency around pkg/store/.lock").
  ## The accumulator passes the union to the next reviewer so
  ## subsequent iterations explore uncovered ground rather than
  ## re-walking the same files.
  scanned_areas: string[]

## streak_check relays approved/blockers/fix_plan/family from its
## input (the current reviewer's verdict) and computes a
## deterministic stop signal based on the previous reviewer's
## verdict. The `family` passthrough lets the fix routing pick the
## same-family fixer so the fix session can inherit the reviewer's
## context (and benefit from prompt-cache hits).
##
## Soft-approval: a low-confidence rejection (`approved=false` AND
## `confidence=="low"`) is treated as approved for streak/fix
## routing purposes. The reviewer's own uncertainty isn't a strong
## enough signal to trigger a fix cycle and risk a false-positive
## loop.
##
## cumulative_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
## ALL prior iterations (both families). The accumulator pattern
## relies on `outputs.streak_check` resolving to the PREVIOUS
## iteration's output during the current expression evaluation
## (rs.outputs is updated AFTER execCompute completes), so the
## expression `unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas,
## input.scanned_areas))` produces a monotonically growing union.
## On the first iteration `outputs.streak_check` is nil → concat
## treats it as empty → result == unique(input.scanned_areas).
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_scanned_areas: string[]

schema fix_input:
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

schema commit_output:
  type: string [enum: "feat", "fix", "refactor", "test", "docs", "chore"]
  scope: string
  subject: string
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  committed: bool

schema commit_tool_input:
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  workspace_dir: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

## ─── Nodes : Feature Dev Phase ──────────────────────────────────

## survey_existing is the gap-driven entry point. It grounds the
## planner in the partial implementation referenced by the gap spec
## by reading the implemented surfaces and emitting an
## `existing_state` record. Read-only: the prompt already enforces
## "no mutating tools", and `readonly: true` adds the runtime guard.
## session: fresh — this is the first agent in the workflow, so there
## is no parent session to inherit from. plan inherits from here.
agent survey_existing:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bounded session — see act's tool_max_steps note. Survey is a
  ## read-only sweep scoped to the gap spec, so a tighter cap is fine.
  tool_max_steps: 50
  system: survey_existing_system
  user: survey_existing_user
  session: fresh
  readonly: true
  output: existing_state
  ## Persist the survey as a versioned artifact (studio Artifact tab +
  ## `iterion report`) — the operator can read it independently of the
  ## downstream plan/act/commit chain.
  publish: existing_state_artifact

agent plan:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bounded session — see act's tool_max_steps note. Plan is read-only
  ## exploration, so a tighter cap is fine.
  tool_max_steps: 60
  system: plan_system
  user: plan_user
  ## session: inherit from survey_existing — the survey already read
  ## the implemented surfaces; plan benefits from the cached file
  ## context and the reasoning chain. plan_system re-asserts the
  ## read-only contract for this turn.
  session: inherit
  ## Persist the plan as a versioned artifact (studio Artifact tab +
  ## `iterion report`) — no extra LLM call; publish only redirects the
  ## already-computed output. `act` still inherits the plan via the session.
  publish: plan_artifact

agent act:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bound the agentic session (maps to claude --max-turns). Unbounded, a
  ## high/max-effort implementer accretes tool-result context until the CLI
  ## dies ("session ended without result message" — observed ~553 tool
  ## calls, then a doomed resume that wedged in a tool-error loop).
  ## error_max_turns is now a graceful partial stop (see
  ## pkg/backend/delegate/claude_code.go), so the alternating review/fix
  ## loop completes anything this cap truncates instead of crashing.
  tool_max_steps: 120
  system: act_system
  user: act_user
  session: inherit

agent simplify:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bounded session — see act's tool_max_steps note.
  tool_max_steps: 50
  user: simplify_user
  session: inherit

## ─── Nodes : Commit ─────────────────────────────────────────────

## prepare_commit forks the simplify session so it inherits the
## full gap-fill context (survey, plan, implementation, simplification).
## Read-only: it runs `git status` / `git diff HEAD` to identify
## the file set, then emits a structured commit plan (semantic
## message + files to stage). It never stages or commits.
##
## The downstream `tool commit_changes` does the deterministic
## `git add -- <files> && git commit -m <msg>`. Splitting intent
## (this node) from execution (the tool) means the structured
## output IS the audit record — the operator can replay or
## inspect what was supposed to be committed independently of
## what `git log` shows.
agent prepare_commit:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  output: commit_output
  system: prepare_commit_system
  user: prepare_commit_user
  session: fork
  readonly: true
  capabilities: [board.read, board.create]

## commit_changes is a deterministic shell tool — no LLM. It
## stages exactly the file list produced by prepare_commit (via
## `git add -- <files>`, leveraging iterion's string[]
## substitution from pkg/backend/model/executor.go's
## shellEscapeValue) and commits with the semantic message. The
## guard `git diff --cached --quiet || git commit` skips the
## commit if `git add` ended up staging nothing — e.g. when the
## file list resolved to paths that were already at HEAD.
tool commit_changes:
  command: "git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -- {{input.files}} && (git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}})"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

## ─── Nodes : Review / Fix Loop ──────────────────────────────────

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  ## Reviewer effort is DECOUPLED from the implementer's effort
  ## (ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE drives plan/act/fix) and defaults to
  ## MEDIUM. A max-effort reviewer is pathologically thorough — it always
  ## finds or re-raises *some* blocker, so the "two consecutive
  ## cross-family approvals" gate never closes and the loop oscillates to
  ## the review_loop bound (observed: a spend-cap run ground ~5h / ~$47 /
  ## 9+ rounds at max without converging, even flagging a non-compiling
  ## test a fixer had just added). Medium keeps the reviewer honest about
  ## REAL production issues without the false-positive churn. This is the
  ## reliable convergence dial — tune reviewer strictness here, keep the
  ## implementer at high/max separately.
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_REVIEW:-medium}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  ## When the LLM hits genuine uncertainty (ambiguous spec, missing
  ## context, impossible-to-decide trade-off), it can escalate to
  ## the human running the CLI by emitting `_needs_interaction:
  ## true` + `_interaction_questions: {...}` in its JSON output.
  ## The runtime catches this, pauses, prompts the dev in their
  ## terminal, and re-invokes the reviewer with the answer mapped
  ## into its input — preserving session continuity.
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  ## Explicit backend pin: model "openai/gpt-5.5" only works via the
  ## claw backend. Without this, the auto-resolver falls back to
  ## ITERION_BACKEND_PREFERENCE (default "claude_code,claw") and
  ## routes the node through claude_code, which doesn't recognise
  ## openai/* models — the agent returns a meta-error string instead
  ## of the structured verdict and the schema validator fails the run.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  ## Reviewer effort knob, shared with reviewer_claude via
  ## ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_REVIEW (default MEDIUM) — see reviewer_claude for
  ## the convergence rationale. Medium is also the safe ceiling on the
  ## ChatGPT-forfait gpt-5.5 endpoint: "high" reserves enough reasoning
  ## tokens to blow the per-call cap when combined with non-trivial tool
  ## output (mirrors docs-refresh's 822ec4ac). If you raise
  ## ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_REVIEW above medium, watch the gpt-5.5 cap.
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_REVIEW:-medium}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw backend uses snake_case tool names. Without these the
  ## reviewer can't read the workspace and produces a
  ## "no filesystem access" verdict — the claw runtime exposes
  ## these via tool.RegisterClawBuiltins.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  ## tool_max_steps: 30 → 12. With the build_diff_manifest output
  ## as the reviewer's primary input, the tool budget is purely for
  ## spot-checks against specific files. Tighter cap forces the LLM
  ## to commit to a verdict instead of re-enumerating the diff via
  ## grep (the loop pattern that hit context_length_exceeded on
  ## the 2026-05-26 issue #5 dogfood).
  tool_max_steps: 12
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector.
##
## stop=true iff the current AND previous reviewers (opposite
## families) both APPROVED, where "approved" is HIGH-CONFIDENCE-
## GATED: a rejection still counts as approval unless it carries a
## `confidence: high` blocker. Rationale — in an autonomous loop
## only high-confidence, production-breaking blockers should hold
## up the ship: medium/low concerns are recorded in scanned_areas
## but don't gate, because (a) the operator reviews the final diff
## and (b) two independent reviewers almost always surface SOME
## medium nit each round, so gating on medium makes "two
## consecutive cross-family approvals" statistically unreachable
## (the oscillation that ground a spend-cap run ~5h/$47 without
## converging). High-confidence blockers still reset the streak
## and route to the same-family fixer.
##
## The `approved` passthrough field is the same high-confidence-
## gated value, so the downstream `when approved` edge keeps
## alternating WITHOUT invoking the fixer on medium/low concerns;
## only a `confidence: high` blocker flips approved=false and
## triggers a fix. That is what keeps the loop converging.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    stop: "(input.approved || input.confidence != 'high') && loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence != 'high'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_scanned_areas: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas, input.scanned_areas))"

## Per-family fixers. Each one inherits the SAME-family reviewer's
## session via `session: inherit` + `_session_id` mapping on the
## edge — so the fixer reuses the prompt cache, the workspace files
## already loaded, and the reviewer's reasoning chain. The result
## is one session per loop iteration per family (not two), which
## both shortens latency and dramatically reduces token cost:
## without inheritance every fixer would re-scan the workspace.
agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bounded session — see act's tool_max_steps note.
  tool_max_steps: 80
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## Same escalation contract as the reviewers — the fixer can ask
  ## the dev a question (e.g. clarify the intent of an ambiguous
  ## blocker) instead of guessing.
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  ## See reviewer_gpt comment — same backend pin rationale.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## claw needs the same read/write toolset the reviewer used so
  ## the fixer can actually apply edits.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow feature_gap_fill:
  entry: survey_existing

  ## Run in an isolated git worktree at .iterion/worktrees/<run-id>/.
  ## This shields the user's main working tree from any mutations the
  ## workflow makes, makes prepare_commit's job structurally correct (no
  ## WIP visible to misclassify), and turns failure cleanup into a
  ## one-line `git worktree remove`. See docs / worktree-runs-plan.md
  ## for the artifact-pollution caveat: even in a fresh worktree, the
  ## dev phase can introduce un-gitignored build outputs, so prepare_commit
  ## still has to discriminate — but on a much smaller noise floor.
  worktree: auto

  ## Container isolation on top of the worktree. The `act` / `simplify`
  ## phase runs arbitrary build/test commands (`go test`, `npm install`,
  ## `cargo build`, …) that the bot infers from the project — the worktree
  ## alone doesn't sandbox those.
  ##
  ## Why inline mode (not `mode: auto`)?
  ## The iterion-sandbox-{slim,full} images don't ship `claude` — every
  ## claude_code agent here shells out to the CLI, so post_create MUST
  ## install it. iterion currently drops post_create / mounts / env when
  ## `mode: auto` falls back to the default image (pkg/runtime/sandbox.go),
  ## so we can't combine "auto fallback" with "install claude into the
  ## container". Inline mode lets us pin both the image and the bootstrap
  ## script. Operators wanting a different image just edit this block —
  ## the inline `image:` ref is the single override point.
  ##
  ## Mounting ~/.claude carries the host's OAuth / ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
  ## credentials so the in-container CLI doesn't need a fresh login
  ## each run. Writable because claude_code persists per-session
  ## transcripts under ~/.claude/projects/<hash>/<session>.jsonl and
  ## iterion's formatter-pass resumes them via `claude --resume`.
  sandbox:
    ## `iterion-sandbox-full` = slim + Go + Python 3 + pnpm. Pulled
    ## once, cached locally. Operators with a different toolchain
    ## (Java, Ruby, Elixir, …) point this at their own image — or
    ## switch to slim and add a `devbox install` step in post_create
    ## with the workspace's devbox.json.
    image: "ghcr.io/socialgouv/iterion-sandbox-full:edge"
    user: "1000:1000"
    mounts: ["type=bind,source=${localEnv:HOME}/.claude,target=/home/devbox/.claude,consistency=cached"]
    env:
      CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR: "/home/devbox/.claude"
    ## post_create installs claude_code if absent (the sandbox images
    ## don't ship it). Kept minimal on purpose: anything heavier (a
    ## `devbox install` pulling Nix packages for the workspace's
    ## toolchain, an `npm install` against the project's
    ## package.json, etc.) belongs in the agent's `act` step where
    ## it's observable + has the run's budget rather than dying
    ## silently here on a post_create timeout.
    ##
    ## Gate on `claude --version` (runs the binary), NOT `command -v
    ## claude` (mere existence): `npm install -g` occasionally exits 0
    ## leaving a broken/partial binary (observed: a `claude.exe`
    ## symlink whose target wasn't fully written → `exec format
    ## error` mid-run). `command -v` would see that broken claude and
    ## skip the reinstall forever. We also VERIFY after install and
    ## exit 1 on failure so a still-broken claude fails post_create
    ## (a clean sandbox-setup error the dispatcher retries with a
    ## fresh container) instead of failing cryptically on the first
    ## claude_code node. See native:c6d93a2a.
    post_create: "set -e; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || sudo npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code@latest; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || { echo 'claude install verification failed' >&2; exit 1; }"

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "4h"
    max_cost_usd: 120

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## ═══ Phase 1 : Survey → Plan → Act → Simplify ═════════════════
  ## All four nodes share one Claude Code session via
  ## `session: inherit` on plan/act/simplify. Survey emits the
  ## `existing_state` record (also pulled into plan's user prompt
  ## as `{{outputs.survey_existing}}`); plan emits text only;
  ## act executes the plan in the same conversation; simplify
  ## invokes the native /simplify skill on the freshly-modified
  ## code.
  survey_existing -> plan with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.survey_existing._session_id}}"
  }
  plan -> act with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.plan._session_id}}"
  }
  act -> simplify with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.act._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Hand off to the alternating review/fix loop. Reviewers run
  ## with `session: fresh` (re-scan the workspace independently)
  ## so they aren't biased by the dev session's reasoning chain.
  simplify -> alt

  ## ═══ Phase 2 : Alternating Review / Fix Loop ══════════════════
  ## Verbatim from whole_improve_loop/main.bot (entry was alt).
  ##
  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## Each reviewer receives the OTHER family's most recent fixer
  ## pushback so it knows which items to skip — the alternation
  ## guarantees the cross-family pushback comes from the previous
  ## iteration's fixer of the opposing family. On the first
  ## iteration both `outputs.fix_*` are empty → fields render as
  ## empty strings and the prompt's "ne re-flague pas ces items"
  ## section is harmless.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## Both reviewers feed into streak_check. The loop is attached
  ## here so the runtime snapshots the reviewer's verdict as
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output` for the NEXT iteration to
  ## inspect — eliminating the manual `previous_verdict` relay.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.scanned_areas}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 3 : Commit on streak success ═══════════════════════
  ## Cross-family double-approval reached. prepare_commit (forked
  ## from simplify) emits the structured commit intent;
  ## commit_changes deterministically applies it.
  streak_check -> prepare_commit when stop with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.simplify._session_id}}"
  }

  prepare_commit -> commit_changes with {
    full_message: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.full_message}}",
    files: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.files}}",
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  commit_changes -> done

  ## Otherwise approved (no streak yet, OR a non-high-confidence
  ## rejection treated as soft-approved, OR rejection without concrete
  ## blockers — see below): keep alternating without fixing.
  ## Expression form is shown here both to demonstrate the new
  ## syntax and so future authors can extend the predicate (e.g.
  ## tighten the soft-approval condition) by enriching the
  ## quoted expression.
  ##
  ## NOTE: this edge does NOT carry `review_loop` so the loop
  ## counter (and the previous_output snapshot) is incremented
  ## ONCE per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edge above. The
  ## cycle is still bounded because that edge IS loop-bearing.
  streak_check -> alt when "approved"

  ## High-confidence rejection WITH concrete blockers: route
  ## to the SAME-family fixer so it can inherit the reviewer's
  ## session (one session per iteration per family — see
  ## fix_claude / fix_gpt comments). `_session_id` reads directly
  ## from the most recent reviewer output rather than going through
  ## streak_check, because compute passthrough strips the
  ## underscore-prefixed metadata fields.
  ##
  ## The `length(blockers) > 0` guard avoids invoking the fixer
  ## when the reviewer rejected on coverage grounds alone (e.g.
  ## "cumulative coverage is partial at iteration 0/15") with no
  ## production-blocking issue identified. In that case the fixer
  ## has nothing to fix — burning a session round-trip and tokens
  ## (~$0.15/$0.43 observed in vibe_review run_1777560043656) only
  ## to push back. The unconditional alt fallthrough below picks
  ## those up so alternation continues without a wasted fix call.
  ##
  ## Edge order matters: iterion evaluates conditional edges top-
  ## down, first match wins. We list both family-specific fixers
  ## before the unconditional `done` fallthrough so loop-exhaustion
  ## still terminates cleanly.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name so its counter doesn't
  ## interfere with the review_loop snapshot semantics. Sized large
  ## enough to allow review_loop to be the binding constraint. Both
  ## fixers share the loop counter — total fix attempts across both
  ## families are capped at 20.
  fix_claude -> alt as recovery_loop(20)
  fix_gpt    -> alt as recovery_loop(20)

  ## Loop exhaustion fallbacks: when a bounded loop hits its limit
  ## the loop-bearing edges above are skipped and execution falls
  ## through to these terminal edges. Route to `fail`, NOT `done`:
  ## exhausting the review/recovery loop WITHOUT streak_check ever
  ## firing `stop` means no convergence and no commit — reporting
  ## `finished` there is a silent empty success, and the dispatcher
  ## would mark the ticket done/review as if work landed. `fail` is
  ## non-resumable so a deterministic non-convergence isn't
  ## re-dispatched in a loop. Legit success is
  ## streak_check (stop) → prepare_commit → commit_changes → done.
  reviewer_claude -> fail
  reviewer_gpt    -> fail
  fix_claude      -> fail
  fix_gpt         -> fail
  ## streak_check's catch-all routes back to `alt` (not a terminal) so
  ## an unmatched conditional state (e.g. a hallucinated family that
  ## escapes the enum, or any future expression edge case) keeps
  ## the loop cycling rather than silently terminating. The bounded
  ## review_loop counter on the reviewer→streak_check edges still
  ## guarantees the workflow eventually exits — exhaustion routes
  ## via the reviewer→fail fallthrough above.
  streak_check    -> alt
